Importing data for cumulative fatalities, suspected cases by country, confirmed cases by country

fatalitiesByCountry <- read.csv("Data Files/CEID Wuhan Coronavirus - Timeline of Key Events - Cumulative fatalities reported by country.csv")

confirmedCasesByCountry <- read.csv("Data Files/CEID Wuhan Coronavirus - Timeline of Key Events - Cumulative case reports by country - confirmed.csv")

chinaProvinceData <- read.csv("Data Files/china-province-data - cases.csv")

#Changing dates into YYYY-MM-DD format
fatalitiesByCountry$Date <- mdy(fatalitiesByCountry$Date)
confirmedCasesByCountry$Date <- mdy(confirmedCasesByCountry$Date)
chinaProvinceData$Date <- mdy(chinaProvinceData$Date)
## Warning: 2 failed to parse.
#removing "sources and contributor columns"
fatalitiesByCountry <- fatalitiesByCountry %>% select(-Sources, -Contributor)
confirmedCasesByCountry <- confirmedCasesByCountry %>% select(-Sources, -Contributor)

Creating a sum column of total new cases or fatalities per recorded day

fatalitiesByCountry <- fatalitiesByCountry %>% replace(is.na(.), 0) %>% mutate(sum = rowSums(.[2:3]))

#renaming cumulative death column "sum" to "totalDeaths"
fatalitiesByCountry <- fatalitiesByCountry %>% rename(totalDeaths = sum)

confirmedCasesByCountry <- confirmedCasesByCountry %>% replace(is.na(.), 0) %>% mutate(sum = rowSums(.[2:28]))

#renaming cumulative confirmed column "sum" to "totalConfirmedCases"
confirmedCasesByCountry <- confirmedCasesByCountry %>% rename(totalConfirmedCases = sum)

Created a loop function to calculate incidence cases

#John Vinson assisted with code for function

incidence.fun = function(cum.dis.vec){
output = 0

for(i in 1:length(cum.dis.vec)){
  out.temp = cum.dis.vec[i+1] - cum.dis.vec[i]

  output = append(output, out.temp)
}

output = head(output, -1)

}

#When new countries report first cases, the number of columns [,X:X] for the script to run through needs to be adjusted
incidenceConfirmedCases <- data.frame(lapply(confirmedCasesByCountry [,2:31],incidence.fun))

#adding date to incidence dataframe and renaming the column to "Date"
incidenceConfirmedCases <- cbind(confirmedCasesByCountry$Date,incidenceConfirmedCases)
incidenceConfirmedCases <- incidenceConfirmedCases %>% rename(Date=`confirmedCasesByCountry$Date`)

Global Cumulative Fatality Curve

fatalitiesByCountry %>% ggplot(.,aes(x=Date, y=totalDeaths, label=totalDeaths)) + geom_point() + theme(axis.text.x=element_text(angle=45,hjust=1)) + ylab("Global Cumulative Deaths") +geom_text(aes(label=totalDeaths),hjust=0.5, vjust=-0.5, size=3.25) + scale_x_date(breaks='2 day')

Global Epidemic Curve (Incidence Data) - Confirmed Cases

#data presented as geom_col
incidenceConfirmedCases %>% ggplot(., aes(Date, totalConfirmedCases)) + geom_col() + theme(axis.text.x=element_text(angle=45,hjust=1)) + ylab("Global Incidence - Number of New Confirmed Cases") + scale_x_date(breaks='2 day')

China Epidemic Curve (Incidence Data) - Confirmed Cases

Cumulative number of countries with confirmed cases over time

#John Vinson assisted with code

case.country.df = as.data.frame(confirmedCasesByCountry>0)*1 #Create a df that is 0 and 1s, where 1 means that there was greater than 0 cases in that country on that date; this will make the date column all 1s because the date is greater than 0 (logical statement), which means we need to take that off before we can do the row sums 

case.country.df=case.country.df[,-1] #remove the date column

cum.country = rowSums(case.country.df) #do the row sums, which creates a vector that is the cumulative number of cases (at each date but the date is not added back yet.)

cum.country.date = data.frame(Date=confirmedCasesByCountry[,1], cum.count = cum.country)  #This the the df of the cumlative number of countries that have confirmed cases by date. We've attached the date to the df since we need that info and we extract it from the initial df (confirmedCasesByCountry).


#plotting cumulative number of countries with positive cases for Coronavirus over time. Note that here Diamond Princess is listed as its own "country" given it isn't claimed by a country for confirmed cases.
cum.country.date %>% ggplot(., aes(Date, cum.count)) + geom_col() + theme(axis.text.x=element_text(angle=45,hjust=1)) + ylab("Cumulative # of Countries with Confirmed Cases") + scale_x_date(breaks='2 day')
